00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:18.010
Over the last four decades,
sport media scholars

00:03:18.010 --> 00:03:20.440
have amassed an increasingly
sophisticated body

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:22.630
of knowledge regarding
the symbiotic connections

00:03:22.630 --> 00:03:24.740
among sport, gender, and power.

00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:26.710
We moved beyond
descriptive content

00:03:26.710 --> 00:03:29.140
analysis-driven
studies, which examined

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:32.140
the frequency of coverage given
to women's and men's sports,

00:03:32.140 --> 00:03:34.720
to scholarly lines of
inquiry that were grounded

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:36.940
in critical feminist theory.

00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:38.830
This particular
analytic framework

00:03:38.830 --> 00:03:40.450
argues that society
is structured

00:03:40.450 --> 00:03:43.870
around a series of inequitable
relationships of power

00:03:43.870 --> 00:03:47.410
where women are systematically
devalued and marginalized.

00:03:47.410 --> 00:03:50.230
We made the empirical
and theoretical case

00:03:50.230 --> 00:03:53.680
that sports serve as an ideal
site for the connections

00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:57.370
between gender and power because
sport vigilantly maintains

00:03:57.370 --> 00:04:00.250
gender as hierarchically
ordered, but more

00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:03.310
importantly grounded
in the physical body

00:04:03.310 --> 00:04:05.740
and thus perceived
as biologically,

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:07.960
meaning inherently, based.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:10.630
We also argue that media
representations play a critical

00:04:10.630 --> 00:04:13.060
role in perpetuating
these notions

00:04:13.060 --> 00:04:16.180
of a biologically-based,
gendered hierarchy--

00:04:16.180 --> 00:04:17.992
where in spite of
the enormous progress

00:04:17.992 --> 00:04:20.200
that has been made two
generations removed from Title

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:23.290
IX, women remain
second-class citizens in one

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:26.620
of the most powerful economic,
social, and political

00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:29.630
institutions on this planet.

00:04:29.630 --> 00:04:33.170
In some, as Mike Messner has
insightfully pointed out,

00:04:33.170 --> 00:04:36.770
female athletes and media
representations of their body

00:04:36.770 --> 00:04:41.327
became and remain
contested terrain.

00:04:41.327 --> 00:04:42.910
Let me just take a
few minutes to talk

00:04:42.910 --> 00:04:45.250
about what we, as
sport media scholars,

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:47.590
have amassed again over
the last forty years.

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:50.290
And we've found two
overarching patterns

00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:53.110
of media representations
given to women's sports.

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:56.800
First, female athletes are
significantly underrepresented

00:04:56.800 --> 00:05:00.640
in that, for example, even
though 43% of all scholarship

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.970
athletes in college sports
nationwide are women,

00:05:03.970 --> 00:05:07.540
they receive only about 2%
to 4% of overall coverage

00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:11.050
across the vast and ubiquitous
sport media landscape.

00:05:11.050 --> 00:05:13.300
And Mike Messner's work,
his longitudinal work,

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:14.620
will point that out.

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:17.740
Second, within this
coverage, female athletes

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:20.350
are significantly
more likely than males

00:05:20.350 --> 00:05:24.070
to be portrayed off the court,
out of uniform, and in highly

00:05:24.070 --> 00:05:25.780
sexualized poses.

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:27.520
Let me just give you
a couple of examples

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:28.700
of what I mean by that.

00:05:38.090 --> 00:05:41.050
That's also Lindsey Vonn.

00:05:41.050 --> 00:05:43.170
And next, from the
team sport of soccer.

00:05:54.377 --> 00:05:55.960
And then look at how
you feel when you

00:05:55.960 --> 00:05:57.126
see that they're juxtaposed.

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:09.430
So let me close by
highlighting the impacts

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:11.290
of these kinds of images.

00:06:11.290 --> 00:06:12.880
I began my remarks
by pointing out

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:15.340
that sports serves as a
critical site for reproducing

00:06:15.340 --> 00:06:17.710
notions of gender and
power differences.

00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:20.350
But what is often overlooked--
and this is absolutely

00:06:20.350 --> 00:06:22.780
essential for any
analysis going forward--

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:25.810
is how sports can also
serve as a critical site

00:06:25.810 --> 00:06:29.680
for subverting these very
ideologies and practices.

00:06:29.680 --> 00:06:32.140
When media images and
narratives emphasize women

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:35.260
as highly skilled and
physically powerful athletes,

00:06:35.260 --> 00:06:38.440
they are directly
challenging and profoundly

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:40.630
threatening to
belief systems that

00:06:40.630 --> 00:06:44.220
have and continue to relegate
sports women to the sidelines.

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:46.570
And that is because when we
sexualize female athletes,

00:06:46.570 --> 00:06:50.320
it takes away from an incredibly
powerful and reaffirming moment

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:52.720
of women's physical
capacities and turn it

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:55.420
into something that is
a moment of triviality

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:57.040
and marginalization.

00:06:57.040 --> 00:06:58.900
I would suggest to
you that until we

00:06:58.900 --> 00:07:03.370
see a plethora of images that
reflect the reality of women's

00:07:03.370 --> 00:07:06.580
participation, they will
never receive the full respect

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:09.970
and admiration that they
not only richly deserve,

00:07:09.970 --> 00:07:11.350
but that they have also earned.

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:11.850
Thank you.

